{
  "local_port": 54036,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you locate the name of a proxy server?",
  "response": "To locate the name of a proxy server, you'll need to follow these steps:\n\n1. Check your network settings:\n   - On Windows, go to Control Panel > Internet Options > Connections > LAN settings\n   - On Mac, go to System Preferences > Network > Advanced > Proxies\n   - On Linux, it depends on your distribution, but you can often find it in Network Manager settings\n\n2. Look for proxy configuration:\n   - If a proxy is set up, you should see the server address and port number\n\n3. Check browser settings:\n   - In Firefox: Options > General > Network Settings > Settings\n   - In Chrome: Settings > Advanced > System > Open computer proxy settings\n\n4. Examine environment variables:\n   - On Windows: Look for HTTP_PROXY or HTTPS_PROXY in System Properties > Advanced > Environment Variables\n   - On Unix-like systems: Use the `echo` command to check these variables, e.g., `echo $HTTP_PROXY`\n\n5. Check your network's documentation:\n   - If you're on a corporate or institutional network, they may provide proxy server details\n\n6. Use command-line tools:\n   - On Windows: `netsh winhttp show proxy`\n   - On Unix-like systems: Try `env | grep -i proxy` or check the output of `curl -v google.com`\n\n7. Examine your system's configuration files:\n   - Look for proxy settings in files like `/etc/environment` or `/etc/profile` on Unix-like systems\n\n8. Check with your network administrator:\n   - If you're on a managed network, they can provide the proxy server details\n\nRemember, the exact method to find the proxy server name can vary depending on your operating system, network setup, and whether you're using a system-wide proxy or one configured just for a specific application.",
